# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vectorscope
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vectorscope/180-line-television-system] The Berlin Summer Olympic Games were televised, using both closed-circuit 375-line fully electronic iconoscope-based cameras and 180-line intermediate film cameras transmitting to Berlin, Hamburg, Munich, Nuremberg, and Bayreuth via special Reichspost long-distance cables in August 1936.
[src:vectorscope/180-line-television-system] In Berlin, twenty-eight public 180-line television rooms were opened for anybody who did not own a television set.
[src:vectorscope/180-line-television-system] After February 1937, both 180- and 375-line systems were replaced by a superior, 441-line system.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] TV cameras were based on the iconoscope, the primary camera tube used in American broadcasting from 1936 until 1946, when it was replaced by the image orthicon tube.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] Earlier cameras used special spotlights or spinning disks to capture light from a single very brightly lit spot, and were not suitable for broadcasting of outdoor live events.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] This early standard was soon replaced by 441-line systems.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] 343-line broadcasts where introduced by RCA and NBC on November 6, 1936.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] Tests started the previous year from New York City (W2XF on the Empire State Building), where NBC converted a radio studio in the Rockefeller Center for television use.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] Several prototype TV sets were produced by RCA in 1936, but none was available commercially.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] Broadcasts were limited to public demonstrations in New York City (RCA) and Philadelphia (Philco) - to be exact, Philco demonstrated a 345-line system, but in practice both systems were identical.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] The 343-line system was proposed for FCC approval by the Radio Manufacturers Association (RMA) in December 1937.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] Broadcasts were phased out the following year, in favor of a 441-line system.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] A a similar 343-line system was tested in the Soviet Union (Moscow) from 1937 onwards.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] RCA provided broadcast equipment and documentation for the TV sets, that were then produced locally.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] The system was adapted for 50 Hz mains electricity, with a field rate of 50 Hz.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] The first experimental transmissions happened on March 9, 1937, followed by regular broadcasts on December 31, 1938.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] In 1939, a 343-line system was under development in Poland, publicly demonstrated during the Warsaw Radio Exhibition on August.
[src:vectorscope/343-line-television-system] Regular operations were planned for the beginning of 1940, but work stopped due to the outbreak of World War II.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] 375-line (50 fps, interlaced) television was demonstrated in 1936 on the Berlin Funkausstellung.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The system used electronic cameras for live exterior broadcasts.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The system was also used on experimental transmissions of the 1936 Summer Olympics (along with the 180-line system), using the Telefunken Iconoscope camera.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] A transmitter was setup in Berlin-Witzleben, broadcasting at 42.9 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The Reichspost distributed the signal to major cities across Germany using cables.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] After the Games transmissions continued to viewing rooms installed on post offices.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] Philips presented a radio/TV combo receiver for the system at the 1937 Berlin Funkausstellung, and Loewe also had a receiver available.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] In the same year Telefunken demonstrated the 375-line system at the Paris Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne, displaying images taken from the exhibition's pavilion terrace.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] In Italy 375-line television transmissions were undertaken by Arturo Castellani in 1937, with daily broadcasts from Rome, between 6pm and 9:30pm on 6.9 meters (43.45 MHz) with a power of 2 kW.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] In the spring of 1940, CBS staff engineer Peter Goldmark devised a system for color television, hoping to gain advantage regarding NBC and its black-and-white RCA system.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The new system proposed by CBS was based on field sequential color and incompatible with existing sets but "gave brilliant and stable colors", while NBC developed a black and white compatible color TV system that was "crude and unstable but compatible".
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The system was tested from CBS station WCBW New York, on June 1, 1941.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] In 1945 CBS demonstrates color broadcast using test equipment and a 10 MHz bandwidth UHF channel.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] Eventually it was shown to the general public on January 12, 1950, as the 405-line Field-Sequential Color System (FSC).
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The vertical resolution was 77% of monochrome, and the horizontal resolution was 54% of monochrome.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The Federal Communications Commission adopted it on October 11, 1950, as the standard for color television in the United States, but it was later withdrawn.
[src:vectorscope/375-line-television-system] The concept was revived by NASA in 1969 for the Apollo color TV cameras.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The **405-line** monochrome analogue television broadcasting system was the first fully electronic television system to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The number of television lines influences the image resolution, or quality of the picture.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] It was introduced with the BBC Television Service in 1936, suspended for the duration of World War II, and remained in operation in the UK until 1985.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] It was also used between 1961 and 1982 in Ireland, as well as from 1957 to 1973 for the Rediffusion Television cable service in Hong Kong.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] 405-line was approved as **System A** in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Sometimes called the **Marconi-EMI system**, it was developed in 1934 by the EMI Research Team led by Isaac Shoenberg.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The figure of 405 lines had been chosen following discussions over Sunday lunch at the home of Alan Blumlein.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The system used interlacing; EMI had been experimenting with a 243-line all-electronic interlaced system since 1933.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In the 405 system the scanning lines were broadcast in two complementary fields, 50 times per second, creating 25 frames per second.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The actual image was 376 lines high and interlaced, with additional unused lines making the frame up to 405 lines to give the slow circuitry time to prepare for the next frame; in modern terms it would be described as *"376i"*.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] At the time of its introduction the 405-line system was referred to as *"high definition"* – which it was, compared to earlier systems, although of lower definition than 625-line and later standards.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In the United States, the FCC had briefly approved a 405-line color television standard in October 1950, which was developed by CBS.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The CBS system was incompatible with existing black-and-white receivers.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] It used a rotating color wheel, reduced the number of scan lines from 525 to 405, and increased the field rate from 60 to 144, but had an effective frame rate of only 24 frames per second.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In 1934, the British government set up a committee (the "Television Committee") to advise on the future of TV broadcasting.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The committee recommended that a "high definition" service (defined by them as being a system of 240 lines or more) should be run and established by the BBC.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The recommendation was accepted and tenders were sought from industry.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Two tenders were received: one from the Baird company offering a 240-line mechanical system, and the other from EMI offering a 405-line all-electronic one.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The Television Committee advised that they were unable to choose between the two systems and that both tenders should be accepted, the two systems to be run together for an experimental period.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This became the standard for all British TV broadcasts until the 1960s.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] It soon became apparent that television reception was also possible well outside the original intended service area.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In February 1938, engineers at the RCA Research Station, Riverhead, Long Island, New York, in the US, were able to receive the BBC signal 5,000 km (3,100 mi) away, due to the signal being "bounced" back to earth from the ionosphere.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] A few minutes of programming were recorded on 16mm movie film.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This is now considered to be the only surviving example of pre-war live British television.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The images recorded included two of the original three BBC announcers, Jasmine Bligh and (in a brief shot) Elizabeth Cowell, an excerpt from an unknown period costume drama, and the BBC's station identification transmitted at the beginning and end of the day's programmes.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The BBC temporarily ceased transmissions on 1 September 1939, the day of the German invasion of Poland, for the outbreak of World War II was imminent.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] After the BBC Television Service recommenced in 1946, distant reception reports were received from various parts of the world, including Italy, South Africa, India, the Middle East, North America and the Caribbean.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The BBC lost its monopoly of the British television market in 1954, and the following year the commercial network ITV, comprising a consortium of regional companies, was launched.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The subcarrier frequency was 2.6578125 MHz (525/2 times line frequency) with an "I" signal bandwidth of 500 kHz and a "Q" signal bandwidth of 300 kHz.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Tests with PAL, SECAM and other NTSC subcarrier frequencies were also attempted.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Some of these broadcasts were on UHF (also an experimental technology at the time), while others were carried over the regular VHF network outside of normal broadcasting hours.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In 1964, the BBC launched its BBC2 service on UHF using only a 625-line system, which older sets could not receive.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] For several years BBC1 and ITV transmitted using the 405-line and BBC2 with the 625-line standard; the only way to receive them all was to use a complex "dual-standard" 405- and 625-line, VHF and UHF, receiver.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The introduction of colour on BBC2 in 1967 necessitated an even more complex dual-standard set to receive all three channels with BBC2 in colour.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Over time in 1968 and 1969, the different ITV regional channels and BBC1 switched over to broadcasting on the 625-line as well as the 405-line, a process which once completed meant that only 625-lines were necessary to receive all channels, with dual standard receivers no longer necessary.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In November 1969, BBC1 and ITV started broadcasting in 625-line PAL colour on UHF.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Their programming was now entirely produced using the new 625-line standard, and thus the 405-line broadcasts served only as a rebroadcast in monochrome for people who did not have the newer receivers and who could only receive BBC1 and ITV.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This situation continued up to 3–4 January 1985, with 405-line VHF receivers only being able to pick up BBC1 and ITV regionals, and in monochrome only, while 625-line UHF receivers could also receive BBC2 and Channel 4/S4C in addition to BBC1 and ITV, and in either colour or monochrome.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] One reason for the long switchover period was the difficulty in matching the coverage level of the new UHF 625-line service with the very high level of geographic coverage achieved with the 405-line VHF service.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The last 405-line transmissions were seen on 4 January 1985 in Scotland; they had been officially shut down one day earlier in the rest of the UK (although they were actually switched off at various points the next day).
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This left only the UHF PAL system in operation in the UK.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The frequencies used by the 405-line system were initially left empty, but were later sold off; they are now used for other purposes, including DAB and trunked PMR commercial two-way radio systems.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Ireland's use of the 405-line system began in 1961 (officially 31st of December 1961), with the launch of Telefís Éireann, but only extended to two main transmitters and their five relays, serving the east and north of the country.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This was because many people in these areas already had 405-line sets for receiving UK broadcasts from Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Telefís Éireann's primary standard was 625-line; it began using this in the summer of 1962, more than two years before the UK had any 625-line channels.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The last 405 line transmitters in the UK and Ireland were shut down in 1985.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The last 405-line relays, in County Donegal, were turned off in 1982; the main transmitters had been shut down in 1978 to free up frequencies for RTÉ 2, and after then the relays had been fed by standards converters from the local 625-line transmitter.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] For the last five years of RTÉ's 405-line simulcasting, a simple orthicon converter was used, essentially a 405-line camera pointed at a 625-line monitor, as the more expensive system converters that RTÉ had previously used were now inoperable.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system was used in the Rediffusion Television cable television service in Hong Kong, established in 1957, making it both the first British colony and the first predominantly Chinese city to have television.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The service of 405-line system ended in 1973, replaced by 625-line PAL system free-to-air broadcast.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] For a brief time in 1939 there were experimental 405-line transmissions from stations in Montrouge in France and Eindhoven in the Netherlands, Czechoslovakia and Switzerland.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] After the U.S. adopted the NTSC 525-line monochrome standard for commercial broadcasting in 1941, subsequent efforts were made to upgrade the standard so that it could also accommodate a "compatible" colour broadcasting system.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This system was a field-sequential colour system which electronically transmitted a 405 lines, 144 fields per second monochrome picture.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Colour was provided mechanically by means of a synchronized rotating transparent Red-Green-Blue disk, which was placed in front of the receiver screen.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Regular broadcast channels were used to transmit the 405-line system signals, but the millions of existing NTSC 525-line television receivers could only correctly process the audio portion of these transmissions, so unless these sets were modified they would only display a jumbled picture.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] CBS aired a variety show special entitled *Premiere* on 25 June 1951 to officially launch commercial 405-line colour broadcasting, but just four months later CBS ended its colour broadcasts.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] CBS's efforts were hindered from the beginning by a widespread lack of acceptance, and the ultimate setback came at the end of the year when the U.S. government temporarily banned the manufacture of colour televisions, ostensibly to conserve resources during the Korean War.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In 1953, the FCC rescinded its approval of the CBS 405-line colour system.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In its place it approved a newly improved and now satisfactory second NTSC 525-line standard which had been developed by RCA.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] It provided for colour broadcasting yet remained compatible with existing 525-line monochrome sets.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] 405-line is System A in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The audio uses amplitude modulation rather than the frequency modulation in use on modern analogue systems.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In addition, the system was broadcast in an aspect ratio of 5:4 until 3 April 1950, when it changed to the more common 4:3 format.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] All System A transmitters used vestigial sideband transmission, with the single exception of Alexandra Palace in London, which closed down in 1957 when it was replaced by Crystal Palace.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Secondly, the smoothing (filtering) of power supply circuits in early TV receivers was rather poor, and ripple superimposed on the DC could cause visual interference.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] However, the main problem was the susceptibility of the electron beam in the CRT being deflected by stray magnetic fields from nearby transformers or motors.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] If the picture was locked to the mains frequency, this interference would at least be static on the screen and thus relatively unnoticeable.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The very earliest TV sets used a mains transformer; care had to be taken in design to prevent the transformer's stray magnetic field from disturbing the electron beam in the CRT.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] An interlaced system requires accurate positioning of scanning lines so the horizontal and vertical timebase must be in a precise ratio.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This is done by passing the one through a series of electronic divider circuits to produce the other.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Therefore, there has to be a straightforward mathematical relationship between the line and field frequencies, the latter being derived by dividing down from the former.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The technology constraints of the 1930s meant that this division process could only be done using small integers, preferably no greater than 7, for good stability.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The number of lines was odd because of 2:1 interlace.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system used a vertical frequency of 50 Hz (standard AC mains supply frequency in Britain) and a horizontal one of 10,125 Hz (50 × 405 ÷ 2 or, using the frame rate, 25 x 405), with 405 being derived from (3 × 3 × 3 × 3 × 5).
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] A few 405-line videotapes still survive.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] However, the majority of surviving 405-line programmes are in the form of black and white film telerecordings, usually with optical soundtracks.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Occasionally video re-recording would be employed instead, with a 625-line camera pointing at a 405-line monitor.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This preserves the original 50-field interlaced format, but with some geometrical distortions owing to the curvature of the CRT monitors used at the time.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] 405-line programming may be recorded and played on an unmodified VHS or Betamax video recorder, as long as the input to the recorder is baseband rather than RF.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Thus, various modern video recordings of 405-line programming also exist.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Betamax was sometimes preferred for this, as the dropout compensator could be switched off on certain models for use with PCM digital audio decoders.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] When used with vestigial sideband filtering, the total bandwidth of a 405-line TV channel is 5 MHz, significantly less than the 8 MHz required by the 625-line System I, which replaced it in Britain.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Systems in other countries used anything between six and fourteen megahertz of bandwidth per channel.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The use of VHF frequencies combined with the narrow vision bandwidth — AM signals (at VHF low band frequencies) are less affected by noise as bandwidth is reduced — meant that 405-line signals could be received well even under marginal conditions.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Therefore, it was possible to cover virtually all of the UK with a relatively small number of transmitting stations.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The use of AM (rather than FM) for sound and the use of positive (rather than negative) video modulation made 405-line signals very prone to audible and visible impulse interference, such as that generated by the ignition systems of vehicles.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Such interference manifested itself as a loud popping on sound and large bright spots on the picture, which viewers found much more noticeable than the dark spots encountered when such interference is encountered on a signal using negative video modulation.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] With positive modulation, interference could easily be of similar amplitude to the sync pulses (which were represented by 0–30% of the transmitter output).
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The early time-base circuits were less able to discriminate between the signals and the picture would break up.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] By contrast, in negative modulation sync, pulses represent peak transmitter output (70–100% output).
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] As a result, impulse interference would cause visual dark spots before it was large enough to affect the synchronisation of the picture.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] If the interference was large enough, the picture was probably unwatchable anyway.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The later introduction of flywheel sync circuits rendered the picture much more stable, but these could not have alleviated some of the problems with positive modulation.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Almost all television systems that succeeded the 405-line system adopted negative modulation for this reason alone.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] First-generation AGC merely detected the average value of the transmitted signal; however, due to the positively modulated carrier, peak power represented peak white – not guaranteed to be present.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Thus for a completely black picture, the AGC circuit would increase the RF gain to restore the average carrier amplitude.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The result was a screen that was not black but mid-grey.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] In fact, the total light output of early TV sets was practically constant regardless of the picture content.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] By the mid-1950s, several manufacturers started to introduce gated-AGC systems to avoid this issue.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] A delayed pulse was derived from the recovered line-sync signal.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This pulse would trigger a gate which would sample the received video signal during the "back porch" which was a guaranteed black-level transmitted between the end of the line-sync pulse and the start of the picture information.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The introduction of negative modulation in later systems simplified the problem because peak carrier power represented sync pulses (which were always guaranteed to be present).
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] A simple peak-detector AGC circuit would detect the amplitude of only the sync pulses, thus measuring the strength of the received signal.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system produced a noticeable 10.125 kHz whistle in many sets, equal to the number of lines per second.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This high-pitched whistle was caused by magnetostriction in the line output transformer.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] This is a common artifact in sets that use a cathode-ray tube.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] While all CRT-based television systems produce such a noise, the higher number of lines per second in later standards produces frequencies (PAL's 15.625 kHz and NTSC's 15.734 kHz) that are at the upper end of the audible spectrum, which not all people are able to hear.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Modern sets using plasma, LCD or OLED display technology are completely free of this effect as they are composed of a million or more individually controllable elements, rather than using a single magnetically deflected beam, so there is no requirement to generate the scanning signal.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The question was raised again from time to time, but a series of tests, conducted during 1952 in cooperation with the British Radio Equipment Manufacturers' Association, confirmed that there was no general need for equalizing pulses.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] On some larger TV screen sizes, the scanned lines were not fat enough to give 100% coverage of the CRT.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] The result was a lined picture with darkness between each horizontal scanned line, reducing picture brightness and contrast.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Larger screen sets often used a spot wobble oscillator, that slightly elongated the scanning spot vertically at high frequency to avoid this line separation effect without reducing horizontal sharpness.
[src:vectorscope/405-line-television-system] Spot wobble was also utilised when making telerecordings of 405-line programmes.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The system's line frequency was 11.025 kHz and the broadcast frequencies were 46.0 MHz for vision and 43.2 MHz for sound, using a 4 MHz channel bandwidth.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Its image aspect ratio was close to 1.15:1.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] A project began in 1938 involving the National Post and several companies including Bosch, Blaupunkt, Loewe, Lorenz, TeKaDe and Telefunken that aimed to produce 10,000 receivers for the television system.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Telefunken marketed the *FE V,* announced in 1936, with a 26 x 21 cm screen and a tuning range of 38-60 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The next year, 1937, the *Heimprojektions-FSE* was introduced, with a larger 50 x 40 cm screen, along with the *FE VI* with a 26 x 21 cm screen.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In 1938, the *Tischfernseher TF 1* was released, with a 20 x 17 cm screen and a tuning range of 40-55 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In 1937, Loewe created the *FE-D*, with a 24x20 cm screen and a tuning range of 35-55 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In 1938, TeKaDe created a single model, the *FS38*, with a 30 x 27 cm screen and a tuning range of 43-52 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] A single-channel TV receiver, the *Einheitsempfänger E1* was created in 1939.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] It had a 29 cm (diagonal) screen, and consumed 185 watts when receiving television signals and 60 watts when receiving audio only.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Only a few units were built before the outbreak of World War II.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Due to the onset of World War II, only about 50 devices were installed in military hospitals and various government departments.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The transmitter's aerials in Berlin were destroyed during an Allied Forces' bombing in November 1943, but the station was also relayed by a special coaxial cable network to "wide screen" public "TV-rooms" (*Fernsehstuben*) so it carried on this way until 1944.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Television programs were mainly for wounded soldiers of the Wehrmacht occupation troops who recovered in the Greater Paris Area hospitals, but they also included French-language shows.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Broadcasts were monitored in the United Kingdom during the Second World War to gather intelligence information from occupied France.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The line frequency was 11.025 kHz with vision broadcast at 46.0 MHz and sound at 42.0 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Aerials were independent for audio and vision at the top of the Eiffel tower, both vertically polarized.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] No gain being obtained from these pre-war basic aerials, the effective radiated power was only the transmitter's peak one, i.e.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] 30 kW which enabled a good reception in a radius of 100 km (62 miles) around Paris.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Frost's WRTH (World Radio TV Handbook) editions at that time, the transmitter's frequencies (42-46 MHz) were listed as channel "F1" or channel "S" (or "Special" channel) in the European Broadcasting Union's official documents.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Broadcasts were due to cease on January 1, 1958, as the 819 lines standard had been adopted in 1948 for the national network.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] However, after a long elections coverage night, most of the 441-line equipment was destroyed by fire on January 3, 1956.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] It was decided to indemnify the 3,000 owners of remaining 441-line sets and to entitle them to reduced rates for their new 819 lines receivers.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Following pre-war tests in 375 lines done by a Turin engineer named Arturo Castellani, broadcasts using the 441-line system began in Italy in 1939 with regular services from Rome using 2 kW power and Milan using 400 W of power in the frequency band of 40-45 MHz.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] As in France technical parameters – VHF frequencies excepted – were identical to those in use in Germany.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Broadcasts were discontinued on May 31, 1940.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The first television tests in Japan were conducted as early as 1926 using a combined mechanical Nipkow disk and electronic Braun tube system, later switching to an all-electronic system in 1935 using a domestically developed iconoscope system.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Television broadcasting started on May 13, 1939, making the country one of the first in the world with an experimental television service.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The broadcasts were in 441-lines with 25 frames/second and 4.5 MHz bandwidth.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In spite of that, because of the beginning of World War II in the Pacific region, this first full-fledged TV broadcast experimentation lasted only a few months.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Regular television broadcasts would eventually start in 1953, using a modified version of the American 525-line standard.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In September 1938 the Radio Manufacturers Association (RMA) recommended the 441-line system developed by RCA and Farnsworth Television.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Tests started a year before, in an attempt to perfect a 343-line system, with RCA executives petitioning the FCC for approval of their new standard.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In early 1938 Philco's experimental transmitter W3XE in Philadelphia was already using the system.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] TV broadcasts were publicly launched in April 1939 by NBC, during the New York World's Fair, using the W2XBS station.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] The first pre-built TV receivers were sold on a very limited basis, mostly in New York City.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Manufacturers included RCA, General Electric, DuMont, and Andrea Radio Corporation.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] By June 1939, regularly scheduled broadcasts were available in New York and Los Angeles.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] By October nineteen TV broadcast licenses had been issued, including stations in New York, Philadelphia (W3XE), Chicago, Washington, Fort Wayne, Cincinnati, Schenectady (W2XB), Los Angeles and San Francisco.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] By November General Electric's station in Schenectady started broadcasts.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] W2XBS in New York broadcast up to fifty-eight hours of programming per month until December 1939, to an estimate of 2,000 receiving sets.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Reception area was a radius of 40-50 miles (80 km) from the Empire State Building.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Following a decision of the NTSC (National Television System Committee), the 525-line standard replaced the 441-line standard on July 1, 1941.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] In the Soviet Union a specification for a 441-line system using 50 interlaced fields per second was proposed in 1940.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Development of this system started in the 1930s, derived from test broadcasts from Moscow, using a 343-line system based on RCA equipment.
[src:vectorscope/441-line-television-system] Due to World War II the 441-line system never reached the broadcast stage.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] The **455-line** standard, also known as 450-line, was a French black-and-white analog television broadcasting norm employed between 1937 and 1939.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] It was later replaced by the 441-line format, which remained in use until 1956.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] In 1931, in Paris, Georges Mandel, the Minister of Posts, provided support to the Compagnie des Compteurs (CdC) in conducting mechanical television experiments.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] Engineer René Barthélémy was granted a studio on Rue de Grenelle, Paris for this purpose.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] The resolution gradually increased from 30 to 60 lines and then to 180 lines by 1935, and the transmitter was located to the Eiffel Tower.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] Robert Jardillier, the next Minister of Posts, launched in 1936 a call for tenders to provide television with higher definition, based on the iconoscope and electronic television.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] A test period would follow and enable the best standard to be chosen.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] Broadcasts became regular from January 4, 1937, from 11 to 11:30 am and 8 to 8:30 pm on weekdays and from 5:30 pm to 7:30 pm on Sundays.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] Grammont performed its tests in 441 lines, the Compagnie Française de Télévision in 450 lines, and Thomson-Houston in 455 lines.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] In July 1937, the administration chose the 455-line system designed by Thomson-Houston, followed by public demonstrations at the International Exposition of Art and Technology in Modern Life.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] Broadcasts using the previous mechanical system continued alongside the new electronic system until April 10, 1938.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] In July 1938, a decree of the Posts, Telegraphs, and Telephones Agency defined the French terrestrial television standard as transmitting on 455 lines VHF (46 MHz, positive visual modulation, 25 frames per second), to be adopted throughout France within three years.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] 455-line TV sets from brands like Pathe-Marconi, Philips, Radioindustrie, CdC, Grammont, and Emyradio began to be sold to the public.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] In 1938, the transmitter, located at the Eiffel Tower, changed to this 455-line format, making it the most advanced and powerful broadcasting system in the world, boasting a transmission power of 30 kW.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] Radiodiffusion Nationale (RN Télévision) starts its broadcasts from Paris, and expansion for other cities like Lyon, Marseille and Bordeaux is planned.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] In the spring of 1939, tests are conducted in Lille.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] The Rue de Grenelle studio closed on July 31, 1939, and after this point, Radiodiffusion Nationale only broadcast films, documentaries, and recorded news using telecine.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] When France entered World War II on September 3, 1939, the military authorities ordered the cessation of broadcasts and took control of the Eiffel Tower transmitter.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] A few broadcasts were still broadcast episodically for transmitter maintenance purposes.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] On June 6, 1940, the French Resistance took action to sabotage this equipment to prevent its use by the Nazis.
[src:vectorscope/455-line-television-system] However, in 1942, the occupying forces decided to repatriate the equipment for their Berlin station and replaced it with 441-line equipment.
[src:vectorscope/525-line-television-system] The system was given their letter designation as **CCIR System M** in the ITU identification scheme adopted in Stockholm in 1961.
[src:vectorscope/525-line-television-system] A similar 625-line system was adopted by countries using a 50 Hz utility frequency.
[src:vectorscope/525-line-television-system] Other systems, like 375-line, 405-line, 441-line and 819-line existed, but became outdated or had limited adoption.
[src:vectorscope/525-line-television-system] The modern standard-definition digital video resolution 480i is equivalent to 525-line and can be used to digitize a TV signal, or playback generating a 525-line compatible analog signal.
[src:vectorscope/525-line-television-system] 525-lines is sometimes mentioned when digitizing analog video, or when outputting digital video in a standard definition analog compatible format.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] A **vectorscope** is a special type of oscilloscope used in both audio and video applications.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Whereas an oscilloscope or waveform monitor normally displays a plot of signal vs. time, a vectorscope displays an X-Y plot of two signals, which can reveal details about the relationship between these two signals.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Vectorscopes are highly similar in operation to oscilloscopes operated in X-Y mode; however those used in video applications have specialized graticules, and accept standard television or video signals as input (demodulating and demultiplexing the two components to be analyzed internally).
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] In video applications, a vectorscope supplements a waveform monitor for the purpose of measuring and testing television signals, regardless of format (NTSC, PAL, SECAM or any number of digital television standards).
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] While a waveform monitor allows a broadcast technician to measure the overall characteristics of a video signal, a vectorscope is used to visualize chrominance, which is encoded into the video signal as a subcarrier of specific frequencies.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The vectorscope locks exclusively to the chrominance subcarrier in the video signal (at 3.58 MHz for NTSC or 4.43 MHz for PAL) to drive its display.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] In digital applications, a vectorscope instead plots the Cb and Cr channels against each other (these are the two channels in digital formats that contain chroma information).
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] A vectorscope uses an overlaid circular reference display, or *graticule*, for visualizing chrominance signals, which is the best method of referring to the QAM scheme used to encode color into a video signal.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The actual visual pattern that the incoming chrominance signal draws on the vectorscope is called the *trace*.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Chrominance is measured using two methods—color saturation, encoded as the amplitude, or gain, of the subcarrier signal, and hue, encoded as the subcarrier's phase.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The vectorscope's graticule roughly represents saturation as distance from the center of the circle, and hue as the angle, in standard position, around it.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] NTSC vectorscopes have one set of boxes for the color bars, while their PAL counterparts have two sets of boxes, because the R-Y chrominance component in PAL reverses in phase on alternating lines.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Another element in the graticule is a fine grid at 270° on the display (i.e., the -U position) used for measuring differential gain and phase.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Often, two sets of bar targets are provided: one for color bars at 75% amplitude and one for color bars at 100% amplitude.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The 100% bars represent the maximum amplitude (of the composite signal) that composite encoding allows for.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] 100% bars are not suitable for broadcast and are not broadcast-safe.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] 75% bars have reduced amplitude and are broadcast-safe.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Some vectorscope models have only one set of bar targets.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The vectorscope can be set up for 75% or 100% bars by adjusting the gain so that the color burst vector extends to the "75%" or "100%" marking on the graticule.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The reference signal used for the vectorscope's display is the color burst that is transmitted before each line of video, which for NTSC is defined to have a phase of 180°, corresponding to the -U position on the graticule.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The actual color burst signal shows up on the vectorscope as a straight line pointing to the left from the center of the graticule.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] In the case of PAL, the color burst phase alternates between 135° and 225°, resulting in two vectors pointing in the half-past-ten and half-past-seven positions on the graticule, respectively.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] In digital (and component analog) vectorscopes, the color burst doesn't exist; hence, the phase relationship between the color burst signal and the chroma subcarrier is simply not an issue.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] A vectorscope for SECAM uses a demodulator similar to the one found in a SECAM receiver to retrieve the U and V color signals, since they are transmitted one at a time, namely the Thomson 8300 Vecamscope.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] On older vectorscopes that use cathode-ray tubes (CRTs), the graticule was often a silk-screened overlay superimposed over the front surface of the screen.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] One notable exception was the Tektronix WFM601 series of instruments, which are combined waveform monitors and vectorscopes used to measure CCIR 601 television signals.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The waveform-mode graticule of these instruments is implemented with a silkscreen, whereas the vectorscope graticule (consisting only of bar targets, as this family did not support composite video) was drawn on the CRT by the electron beam.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Modern instruments have graticules drawn using computer graphics, and both graticule and trace are rendered on an external VGA monitor or an internal VGA-compatible LCD.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Most modern waveform monitors include vectorscope functionality built in, and many allow the two modes to be displayed side-by-side.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] The combined device is typically referred to as a waveform monitor, and standalone vectorscopes are rapidly becoming obsolete.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] In audio applications, a vectorscope is used to measure the difference between channels of stereo audio signals.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] One stereo channel drives the horizontal deflection of the display, and the other drives the vertical deflection.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] A monaural signal, consisting of identical left and right signals, results in a straight line with a gradient of +1.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] Any stereo separation is visible as a deviation from this line, creating a Lissajous figure.
[src:vectorscope/vectorscope] If a straight line appears with a gradient of −1, this indicates that the left and right channels are 180° out of phase.
